-- classes
A class is a logical template.
a blueprint for the code
it doesn't exist in the memory during runtime until
it is loaded.

In professional software, you cannot hardcode data for every user. You need a standardized structure (Class) that
can be reused millions of times. It allows for Modularization—instead of one giant file of code, you break the system
into small, manageable pieces (Objects) that talk to each other.

1.Fields (State) : what data will object hold
2.Methods (Behavior) : what can the object do?


-- objects
An object is physical entity that occupies space in
memory. "new" keyword, telling JVM look at the class(blueprint)
allocate enough memory for its field


Account ac = new Account();

ac is the reference it will stored in the stack
new Account() it will stored in the heap area

-- this
-- this is a reference to the current object
it is used to resolve ambiguity between class's field and constructor parameters

